 Shadow Image: On the Specificity of Early Radiographs and Their Interpretations around 1900 -- tVISUALITY, VISUALIZING, IMAGING -- tInstrument-Aided Vision and the Imagination: The Migration of Worms and Dragons in Early Microscopy* -- tIMAGE NOISE -- tProgrammed Images: Systems of Notation in Seventeenth- and Eighteenth-Century Weaving -- tDIAGRAMMATICS -- tEarly Modern Images of Musical Automata: On Athanasius Kircher’s Trompe-l’Oreille Contemplations in the Quirinal Gardens in Rome -- tPOPULARIZING SCIENCE -- tDrawing and the Contemplation of Nature— Natural History around 1600: The Case of Aldrovandi’s Images -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tTHE AUTHORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn science and technology, the images used to depict ideas, data, and reactions can be as striking and explosive as the concepts and processes they embody—both works of art and generative forces in their own right. Drawing on a close dialogue between the histories of art, science, and technology, The Technical Image explores these images not as mere illustrations or examples, but as productive agents and distinctive, multilayered elements of the process of generating knowledge. Using beautifully reproduced visuals, this book not only reveals how scientific images play a constructive role in shaping the findings and insights they illustrate, but also—however mechanical or detached from individual researchers’ choices their appearances may be—how they come to embody the styles of a period, a mindset, a research collective, or a device. Opening with a set of key questions about artistic representation in science, technology, and medicine, The Technical Image then investigates historical case studies focusing on specific images, such as James Watson’s models of genes, drawings of Darwin’s finches, and images of early modern musical automata. These case studies in turn are used to illustrate broad themes ranging from “Digital Images” to “Objectivity and Evidence” and to define and elaborate upon fundamental terms in the field. Taken as a whole, this collection will provide analytical tools for the interpretation and application of scientific and technological imagery.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aDigital images. 0aScientific illustration. 0aTechnical illustration. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBredekamp, Horst, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBredekamp, Horst, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrons, Franziska, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBruhn, Matthias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDitzen, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDünkel, Vera, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDünkel, Vera, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFischel, Angela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHennig, Jochen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMayer-Deutsch, Angela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Peter N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPratschke, Margarete, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchneider, Birgit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchneider, Birgit, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWeber, Heike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWendler, Reinhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWerner, Gabriele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08i